default3.4 We welcome the Committee’s recommendation that limiting the right to compensation where a claim is grossly exa
defaultggerated should be explored further. A contract of insurance is one of utmost good faith. It is a well established legal principle that if any part of a claim under a contract of insurance is exaggerated or fraudulent, the insurer is entitled to avoid the 
defaultwhole claim. At common law the same principle, notwithstanding the use of statements of truth, does not apply. We would refer the Committee to 
defaultNield v Loveday, Zurich v Haywood 
defaultand 
defaultSummers v Fairclough Homes 
defaultto illustrate the approach adopted at common law
default and where damages have been recovered where there has been significant exaggeration. 
defaultWe would refer the Committee to the Law Commission’s 12
defaultth
default programme of civil justice reform in respect of which the insurance industry is recommending that the law should
default be changed so that damages are not recovered at all in circumstances where there is fraud or fraudulent exaggeration.  
